{{Blurimage|file=Static-assets-upload14348654645550510876.webp|caption=The infamous image of the hallway of the Sparse Alleyway.|hovertext=The Sparse Alleyway.}}

'''Level 877''', predominantly known as "Sparse Alleyway," is a dense area of sparsely spaced, angular labyrinthine passageway. It is surrounded by rusted metal doors hanging from the ceiling. Cantonese calligraphy appears atop some shuttered entrances, usually translating to things like "supermarket" or "restaurant". The floor is composed of tile-like stone designs, with grass growing on the linings of hard stone tiles. This level's walls are constructed of grey concrete, though the greenish-yellow light illuminating the level makes them appear colored. The dim lamps emitting this light are connected by thin, fragile wires that can pose a risk of electrocution.  

There are resources in this area, though their state is often questionable. Wanderers may find stir-fried noodles and boba drinks on tables or seats. Typically, this food will appear half-eaten (by who or what is unclear). Besides the meals, there are little water bottles and empty bags. Rusted wrenches, crumpled plastic straws, and discarded papers with Teochew handwriting are among the items frequently discovered on the ground. In addition, one may come across Hokkien-language periodicals. There are also a few publications sprinkled throughout with writing in Hakka or Cantonese.  

{{Blurimage|width=200px|file=Rdjyfvs28xg61.jpg|caption=One of the rooms found in the alleyway|align=left}}

Auditory anomalies are commonly present within '''Level 877'''. Alongside the monotone buzzing of the level's light fixtures, other noises can be heard; these sounds have occasionally been recognized as news reports, soap operas, dial tone noises, and opening or closing garage doors. Even if one stands completely still, the sources of noise seem to move around them, perpetually out of sight. These sounds, among other factors, result in the alleyways of the level posing a threat to one's sanity. Sanity deterioration symptoms within '''Level 877''' come in many forms; phantom pains, hallucinations, anxiety, paranoia, and sudden fatigue are among the most common.   

While most of the metal doors and gates that make up the level's borders are permanently locked, there are exceptions. Occasionally, one may find an open door leading into a much more well-lit area. The majority of these rooms are fancy restaurants with green tables and chairs. These rooms differ from the alleyways in that the ceiling possesses rectangular white lights and the floor is covered by a large gray rug. The walls are constructed of white stone, and pictures of complex patterns and traditional Chinese inscriptions are impressively hung around the eateries. The restaurants also contain functional bathrooms.

Rooms may vary in size, as the image shows a rare medium-sized eatery; cramped or small restaurants are more typical. These areas smell strongly of traditional Asian food and are the only places at the level where fresh cuisine can be found. While ingredient storage in these rooms is empty and no employees are present, there are often one or more meals prepared at a table, steaming hot. 

<div class="paper" style="font-size: 1.06rem; font-family: Kavivanar; letter-spacing: 0.005rem;">I thought I’d find a safer level this time. Somewhere calm. Somewhere I could finally breathe. Don’t get me wrong, this place isn’t utterly deadly—there are no entities, at least. But the environment... it’s breaking me. I can’t shake the paranoia. It’s like someone’s always there, just out of sight, watching me. The alleys feel alive with that sickly yellowish-green glow, and every step echoes like it’s not just mine.
The only solace I’ve found here is the street food. Somehow, it feels like a tiny pocket of warmth in this cold, desolate place. I don’t know who makes it—maybe it’s the level itself, for all I know. But whoever, or whatever, it is... I’m so grateful. It’s strange how something as simple as fresh food can make me feel human again. I haven’t had a home-cooked meal since I first entered the Lobby, and this isn’t even close. But the taste, the freshness—it’s enough to make me cry.

The restaurants here are almost invisible, tucked away unless their doors are open. You’ll know one’s near when the smell of fresh food finds you. Follow it. Trust me, you’ll want to.

Sincerely,

James
</div>

